        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Baltimore Oct&#91;ober&#93; 9 &#91; author inserted <lb/>&#93; 1883<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Mr. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>I am fully aware what<lb/> large demands on your time&#44; your nu&#45;<lb/>merous correspondents make&#44; but as you<lb/> have heretofore given me such a large<lb/> share of your time and attention I<lb/> am sure that you will not grudge<lb/> me this little. Besides you have a<lb/> right to know how the instruction<lb/> which you gave me&#44; instruction which<lb/> every day I find to be more and<lb/> more valuable&#44; is being added to.<lb/> You will no doubt be pleased to know<lb/> that my teacher Dr. Haupt is not a<lb/> destructive critic and that he is in most<lb/> of his views conservative. Assyrian will<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>claim most of my attention for the<lb/> present and as it contains very nearly<lb/> four hundred syllabic signs&#44; the pre&#45;<lb/>liminary work requires quite an effort<lb/> of the memory. I am also taking up<lb/> Arabic&#44; Ethiopic &#38; Sumeri&#45;Akkadian the<lb/> latter probably though not yet conclusively<lb/> proven to be an Aryan language. These<lb/> with the addition of Sanskrit comprise<lb/> my studies. Hebrew is pronounced<lb/> here in the eastern way&#59; ע &#91;&#63;&#93; an extremely<lb/> strong guttural&#44; also found in Arabic<lb/> &#38; Assyrian. One gets to see all the <lb/> new books &#38; quite a number have<lb/> come our during the last few weeks<lb/></p> 
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>some of which I noted in last week&#91;&#39;&#93;s<lb/> &#34;American.&#34; Dr. Lowe&#91;&#63;&#93; has edited<lb/> the Mishnah of ירושלמי  the 9th<lb/> edition of Gesenius&#91;&#63;&#93; dictionary has just<lb/> appeared  &#40;in German&#41;. Midrash Rabba<lb/> &#40;Debarim&#41; has just been translated into<lb/> German. One of the things that I have<lb/> noticed already is that the Assyrian form<lb/> of a noun almost invariably agrees with<lb/> the Hebrew construct rather than ab&#45;<lb/> solute&#44; with &#91;Hebrew&#93; rather than &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>Trusting that this may find you<lb/> in good health I remain<lb/>
                Your grateful pupil<lb/>
                Cyrus Adler</p>
        </body>
